<p class="lead">The Godwin Repository draws its name from <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Godwin's_law">Godwin's law</a>, which is a brilliant maxim devised by Mike Godwin. Here is how Wikipedia defines it:</p>

<blockquote><p>"As an online discussion grows longer, the probability of a comparison involving Nazis or Hitler approaches 1" —​ that is, if an online discussion (regardless of topic or scope) goes on long enough, sooner or later someone will compare someone or something to Hitler or Nazism.</p></blockquote>

<p>The Godwin Repository is a crowdsourced database that tracks the use of comparisons to Hitler and the Nazis in popular media and the public sphere. As politics become increasingly polarized, rhetoric becomes increasingly sensational and hyperbolic. As Adolph Hitler and Nazi Germany have become two of the few universal references for evil around globe, they have become token references for the evil that occurs when (to quote the venerable <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edmund_Burke">Edmund Burke</a>) good men do nothing.</p>

<p>As an apolitical database, the Repository is an attempt at creating a public record in order to a) highlight the frequency of ridiculous comparisons to Hitler and/or the Nazis in order to acknowledge just how banal and ineffectual they have become and b) to function as a reference database for researchers and writers.</p> 
